    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">灰燼</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">

    <p resp="#CH" modified="2020-11-06T21:31:10.057+09:00">SUBSTANCE that REMAINS AFTER a THING is BURNT. </p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>[[COMMON/RARE]]</p>
<p>[GENERAL/SPECIFIC]</p>
<p>[LASTING/TEMPORARY]</p>
<p>1. The most general word for what is left of something after it is burnt is perhaps the rather rare jìn 燼, and these substances can be cold or still hot.</p>
<p>[GENERAL]</p>
<p>2. Huī 灰 refers specifically to cold ashes.</p>
<p>[SPECIFIC]; [[COMMON]]</p>
<p>3. Wēi 煨 refers to embers that are still very hot.</p>
<p>[SPECIFIC], [TEMPORARY]; [[RARE]]</p>
<p>Compare also SOOT for the dark remnants of something burnt.</p>
<p>NB: Xiè 灺 refers specifically to what is left of candles etc after they are burnt out and came into use in Tang times (Hán Yù).</p>
        </div>
